{"segment_id": "00081", "page_num": 81, "segment": "construct a CFD based on only one or more of the subtypes. For example,\nwe can look at a single CFD that shows just the data for the user story type,\nor we can build a CFD based on just defects, or we can generate a CFD that\ncombines both user stories and maintenance---to just name a few. This\nproperty of CFDs will open up all kinds of avenues of analysis for you. For\nexample, at the portfolio level, you may want to look at data combined\nacross all teams, or you may just want to filter based on an individual team.\nOr maybe you want to filter by release. At the team level, you might want to\nfilter by some other custom field that is particularly relevant to your context\n(as in the “bad data” example from above). All of these activities are\nperfectly ok and I would challenge you to think about what data attributes\nyou might want to collect and then filter on when analyzing your CFDs.\n\nCFDs offer a concise way to simultaneously visualize the three basic\n\nmetrics of flow: WIP, Cycle Time, and Throughput (albeit sometimes in the\nform of averages or approximate averages). You can only be guaranteed to\ncalculate these metrics, however, if your graph obeys all six properties of a\nCFD:\n\nCFD Property #1 is that the top line of a Cumulative Flow Diagram always represents\nthe cumulative arrivals to a process. The bottom line on a CFD always represents the\ncumulative departures from a process.\n\nCFD Property #2 is that due to its cumulative nature, no line on a CFD can ever\ndecrease (go down).\n\nCFD Property #3 is that the vertical distance between any two lines on a CFD is the\ntotal amount of work that is in progress between the two workflow steps represented by\nthe two chosen lines.\n\nCFD Property #4 is that the horizontal distance between any two lines on a CFD\nrepresents the Approximate Average Cycle Time for items that finished between the two\nworkflow steps represented by the chosen two lines.\n\nCFD Property #5 is that the data displayed on a CFD depicts only what has happened\nfor a given process. Any chart that shows any type of projection is not a CFD.\n\nCFD Property #6 is that the slope of any line between any two reporting intervals on a\nCFD represents the exact Average Arrival Rate of the process state represented by the\nsucceeding band.\n\nWith a strong quantitative understanding of CFDs, we move now to a\nmore qualitative analysis---which is really where the predictability rubber\nhits the road.", "source_file": "Actionable_Agile_Metrics_for_Predictability_An_Introduction_-_Daniel_S_Vacanti.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "Flow Metrics and CFDs", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "construct a CFD based on only one or more of the subtypes. CFD Property #2 is that due to its cumulative nature, no line on a CFD can ever\ndecrease (go down). CFD Property #5 is that the data displayed on a CFD depicts only what has happened\nfor a given process.", "l2_summary": "construct a CFD based on only one or more of the subtypes. CFD Property #1 is that the top line of a Cumulative Flow Diagram always represents\nthe cumulative arrivals to a process. The bottom line on a CFD always represents the\ncumulative departures from a process. CFD Property #2 is that due to its cumulative nature, no line on a CFD can ever\ndecrease (go down). CFD Property #3 is that the vertical distance between any two lines on a CFD is the\ntotal amount of work that is in progress between the two workflow steps represented by\nthe two chosen lines. CFD Property #5 is that the data displayed on a CFD depicts only what has happened\nfor a given process.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 80, "segment_id": "00080"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 82, "segment_id": "00082"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": true, "has_diagram": true, "