{"segment_id": "00132", "page_num": 132, "segment": "Figure 10.4: The 95th Percentile Line added to a Scatterplot\nThe 50th, 85th, and 95th percentiles are probably the most popular\n“standard” percentiles to draw. Other percentiles that you will see, though,\ncould include the 30th and 70th. Calculating those percentiles is exactly the\nsame as I have just demonstrated with the others. A Scatterplot with all of\nthese percentile lines is shown in Figure 10.5 (note the 30th percentile is 11\ndays and the 70th percentile is 32 days):", "source_file": "Actionable_Agile_Metrics_for_Predictability_An_Introduction_-_Daniel_S_Vacanti.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "10", "chapter_title": "Introduction to Cycle Time", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Figure 10.4: The 95th Percentile Line added to a Scatterplot\nThe 50th, 85th, and 95th percentiles are probably the most popular\n“standard” percentiles to draw. Other percentiles that you will see, though,\ncould include the 30th and 70th. A Scatterplot with all of\nthese percentile lines is shown in...", "l2_summary": "Figure 10.4: The 95th Percentile Line added to a Scatterplot\nThe 50th, 85th, and 95th percentiles are probably the most popular\n“standard” percentiles to draw. Other percentiles that you will see, though,\ncould include the 30th and 70th. Calculating those percentiles is exactly the\nsame as I have just demonstrated with the others. A Scatterplot with all of\nthese percentile lines is shown in Figure 10.5 (note the 30th percentile is 11\ndays and the 70th percentile is 32 days):", "prev_page": {"page_num": 131, "segment_id": "00131"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 133, "segment_id": "00133"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": true, "has_diagram": true, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["percentile", "percentiles", "figure", "95th", "scatterplot", "30th", "70th", "days"], "content_typ