{"segment_id": "00137", "page_num": 137, "segment": "The Y-axis represents the Cycle Time for an item to complete.\nThe labels and reporting intervals on the chart are at the sole\ndiscretion of the graph’s creator.\n\nA Cycle Time Scatterplot is not a Control Chart. It is not a Run Chart,\neither.\nOne of the best ways to put some structure around Cycle Time\nScatterplot data is to draw percentile lines. Consider starting with the\n50th, 70th, 85th, and 95th percentiles.\nPercentiles have the advantages of being easy to calculate, being\nagnostic of the underlying data distribution, and not being skewed by\noutliers.", "source_file": "Actionable_Agile_Metrics_for_Predictability_An_Introduction_-_Daniel_S_Vacanti.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "10", "chapter_title": "a), but just know that for now the conclusions based on the", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "The Y-axis represents the Cycle Time for an item to complete. A Cycle Time Scatterplot is not a Control Chart. It is not a Run Chart,\neither.", "l2_summary": "The Y-axis represents the Cycle Time for an item to complete. The labels and reporting intervals on the chart are at the sole\ndiscretion of the graph’s creator. A Cycle Time Scatterplot is not a Control Chart. It is not a Run Chart,\neither. One of the best ways to put some structure around Cycle Time\nScatterplot data is to draw percentile lines. Consider starting with the\n50th, 70th, 85th, and 95th percentiles.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 136, "segment_id": "00136"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 138, "segment_id": "00138"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": true, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["cycle", "time", "chart", "scatterplot", "data", "percentiles"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "devops", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": [], "