{"segment_id": "00170", "page_num": 170, "segment": "Figure 13.4: FIFO Pull Order with Always One Expedite on the Board\nAny surprises here (Figure 13.4)? Compared to the previous case (the\n\nrandom pulling case), Expected Cycle Time has increased five days from 60\ndays to 65 days. You can see the Histogram (Figure 13.4) has become much\nmore compact, but there is still a wider spread than when compared to our\nbaseline case (the strict FIFO/no expedites case), and, as I just mentioned,\noverall Cycle Times are longer. Did you expect this to be the worst case yet\nfrom a Cycle Time perspective? You can see that this is only marginally\nworse than the random queuing round---but it is still worse. That is an\ninteresting point that bears a little more emphasis. In this context,\nintroducing an Expedite CoS is worse for predictability than simply pulling\nitems at random. Hopefully you are getting a feel for just how disruptive\nexpedites can be (if you were not convinced already).\n\nBut we are not done yet. There is still one permutation left to consider.\nIn this final experiment, we are going to change our pull policies for\nStandard class items back to random from FIFO. We are going to keep the\nrule of always having one Expedite item on the board. The pull policies for", "source_file": "Actionable_Agile_Metrics_for_Predictability_An_Introduction_-_Daniel_S_Vacanti.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "13", "chapter_title": "Pull Policies", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Figure 13.4: FIFO Pull Order with Always One Expedite on the Board\nAny surprises here (Figure 13.4)? Compared to the previous case (the random pulling case), Expected Cycle Time has increased five days from 60\ndays to 65 days.", "l2_summary": "Figure 13.4: FIFO Pull Order with Always One Expedite on the Board\nAny surprises here (Figure 13.4)? Compared to the previous case (the random pulling case), Expected Cycle Time has increased five days from 60\ndays to 65 days. Did you expect this to be the worst case yet\nfrom a Cycle Time perspective? You can see that this is only marginally\nworse than the random queuing round---but it is still worse. The pull policies for", "prev_page": {"page_num": 169, "segment_id": "00169"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 171, "segment_id": "00171"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": true, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["case", "random", "figure", "fifo", "pull", "expedite", "cycle", "days", "still", "than"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "devops|architecture", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": [], "products": [], "technologies": ["FIFO", "Expedite CoS"], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": true, "metrics": ["Expected Cycle Time", "Cycle Times"], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["FIFO Pull Order", "Expedite CoS Impact", "Cycle Time Analysis"], "key_concepts": ["FIFO pull order", "Expedite CoS", "Expected Cycle Time", "Predictability"], "problem_statement": "Impact of introducing an Expedite CoS on cycle time and predictability in a FIFO pull order system", "solution_approach": null, "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00171", "page_num": 171, "segment": "the Expedites remain the same: they can violate WIP limits and will always\nget pulled in preference to Standard class items.\nNow what do you think will happen?\n\nFigure 13.5: Random Pull Order with Always One Expedite on the Board\nExpected Cycle Time in this scenario (Figure 13.5) has jumped to a\nsimulation-worst 100 days! The spread of our data shown by the Histogram\n(Figure 13.5) is also worrying: Cycle Times range anywhere from 40 days to\n170 days. If that is not variability, then I do not know what is. Remember, in\nthe ideal system of the first case, the range of Cycle Times were 30 to 50\ndays.\n\nLet’s look at all these results side by side (Figure 13.6):", "source_file": "Actionable_Agile_Metrics_for_Predictability_An_Introduction_-_Daniel_S_Vacanti.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "13", "chapter_title": "Pull Policies", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "The spread of our data shown by the Histogram\n(Figure 13.5) is also worrying: Cycle Times range anywhere from 40 days to\n170 days. Remember, in\nthe ideal system of the first case, the range of Cycle Times were 30 to 50\ndays. Let’s look at all these results side by side (Figure 13.6):", "l2_summary": "the Expedites remain the same: they can violate WIP limits and will always\nget pulled in preference to Standard class items. Now what do you think will happen? Figure 13.5: Random Pull Order with Always One Expedite on the Board\nExpected Cycle Time in this scenario (Figure 13.5) has jumped to a\nsimulation-worst 100 days! The spread of our data shown by the Histogram\n(Figure 13.5) is also worrying: Cycle Times range anywhere from 40 days to\n170 days. Remember, in\nthe ideal system of the first case, the range of Cycle Times were 30 to 50\ndays. Let’s look at all these results side by side (Figure 13.6):", "prev_page": {"page_num": 170, "segment_id": "00170"}, "n